        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In band 3 we assume the measured unresolved CO(1-0) signal from PDS456 in 
Yun et al. (2004; 1.45 Jy km/s). We propose to tune the receiver to centre 
on this line, and point to the location of the AGN.

In the C34-5/6 configuration for 0.6-arcsec resolution, and an extent of up to 
3.5-arcsec, we would expect to image 8-30 independent beams on the potential 
extent of the object. Assuming uniform flux distributed between 10 beams, 
this would lead to a flux of about 0.8\,mJy per beam integrated across the line. 
 
In order to obtain significant detections of CO from any fainter regions of the target, 
and to probe the rotation curve or resolved velocity dispersion in the host, 
we propose to achieve a sensitivity of 0.2\,mJy per synthesized beam in each 
50-km/s channel, corresponding to a total signal-to-noise ratio integrated 
across the whole line and target of about 220. Any emission from a broad CO(1-0) 
outflow component would be in addition to this estimate, being missed from the 
earlier OVRO image (Yun et al. 2004; Fig 1-centre). At the expected 
few per cent level, it should be readily detectable, and provide a ratio of 
line strengths in the high-velocity component. 

The host galaxy/AGN  has suspected confirmed structure on a 3.5-arcsec scale, 
and it is likely that fainter structure also lies within 5 arcsec (15 kpc at z=0.18). 
We request 0.6-arcsec resolution that can be easily achieved in the C34-5 
or C34-6 configurations in order to reveal any rotation curve structure in the host, 
and resolve apart CO(1-0) emission from the near-IR detections K1-3 (Fig.\,1) 
and the AGN. All expected structure lies well within the ~52-arcsec primary beam 
at 97GHz.
 
We set up the basebands with one on CO(1-0) and the other three in the 
sidebands for continuum measurements. 
    
The integration time calculator predicts an integration time of 1.96\,hr, and 
a total time of 3.77\,hr.

The corresponding integrated continuum sensitivity in a 7.5-GHz bandwidth in 
dual polarization is 10\,$\mu$Jy (1$\sigma$), which could detect PDS\,456 if 
it is as bright as the expected extrapolated dust flux density of 0.06\,mJy 
derived from SCUBA2 observations at 350GHz. There could be up to 1mJy of 
extrapolated radio emission in addition, which would provide a valuable limit to the 
high-frequency synchrotron emission co-located with the AGN. There will be 
a precise limit to the extended host emission.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
