        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our observation in Band 7 is centred on CO(3-2), to provide the same sensitivity 
and velocity width as in Band 3, and thus to detect this line more significantly 
than CO(1-0) in the excitation cases discussed above. An integrated line strength 
of about  10 Jy.km/s is reasonable, which with the assumptions above would 
correspond to a flux of 5.5mJy per beam across the full width of the line. 
A sensitivity of 0.4mJy per synthesized beam per 50-km/s channel should assure 
more than three times as significant a detection  for CO(3-2) than for CO(1-0), 
with a reasonable expectation of a signal-to-noise ratio of 4 per 
50-km/s channel in each synthesized beam, or 750 integrated over the whole 
line and source. A total signal to noise of 750 should ensure than any broad 
outflow component at the few percent level is readily detected, providing a 
spatially-resolved excitation measure versus CO(1-0) in the outflowing gas. 
 
The 292.06-GHz tuning corresponds to significantly finer angular resolution 
for the same baseline as the band-3 observation.  We would like to detect the 
source at the same resolution for a good comparison, and so we specify 
0.6-arcsec resolution in this science goal in order to allow matched 
observations in the C34-2 configuration. 
 
The issues of spatial resolution are identical to those in Band 3. The other 
three basebands are set to sample the continuum. 
 
The corresponding 280-290-GHz continuum sensitivity (1-sigma) is 28 microJy, 
which should give a very significant detection of the continuum structure 
in the target, which we estimate at 3.0 mJy, giving a 100-sigma continuum 
detection, integrated over the source. This will allow dust 
colour-temperature-emissivity maps to be produced throughout the source versus 
the Band-3 and Band-9 observations, and to be certain of any non-thermal excess
in band 3. 
 
The integration time calculator predicts an on-source integration time of 
33.4 min and a total time of 1.32 hour.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
