        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The highest-frequency observation includes basebands that are tuned to search for both CO(7-6) at 681.29GHz and [CI] at 683.57GHz. If CO(7-6) is excited as moderately as in Danielson et al. (2011), then we would expect an integrated line flux of 8.5 Jy.km/s; if as extreme as Riechers et al. (2011), then we would expect 46 Jy.km/s. We expect comparable fluxes in the [CI] line. 

We propose to reach a sensitivity of 5mJy in a 50km/s channel, to provide matched spectral resolution to the lower-excitation line searches in the most compact configuration C34-1 with 0.57-arcsec resolution, and a reasonable chance of detecting the line in the highly-excited case, and around the nucleus. 

This spectral image can be used to compare in size to the other bands, to reveal internal structure in the continuum emission, including temperature information, as the SED peaks at an observed frequency of 1-3THz, and differences in the emission longwards will only appear in this band (Fig.2-right). We propose to ensure that there is no missed emission by centering this observation with a smaller primary beam midway between the AGN and K1-3 (Fig.1left). 

A 1-sigma sensitivity of 0.24mJy per beam is expected in the 680-GHz continuum, which should ensure a very significant detection of the expected 23mJy flux density (Fig.1 right), providing a spatially resolved image that will highlight the warmest dust. The total integrated signal-to-noise ratio on the continuum source is expected to be about 100. 

Time estimate: 7.8min on source, 40.45 min in total. </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
