    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>PDS456 is a powerful IRAS-detected AGN at a modest redshift (z=0.18). 
We have recently defined its far-IR SED using Herschel and SCUBA2, 
and know that it has a very powerful obscured thermal 
QSO SED, which closely matches the extreme WISE-selected `HotDOGS' at 
the peak of the QSO epoch in both shape and luminosity. In fact, PDS456 is only 
10% fainter than a "HyLIRG". At z=0.18, ALMA's resolution and sensitivity 
can easily resolve the submm SED of PDS456, and reveal whether its 
extreme (~0.3c) AGN outflows are associated with a fast molecular wind. We 
can image its host and any companions, construct many-element 
spectral-index dust maps from 100-700GHz to highlight hotter/cooler regions, 
and reveal any high-frequency AGN radio emission in band-3. Moreover, 
resolved matched-resolution CO line maps and ratios will reveal dynamics, 
putting its extreme luminosity in the context of its host orientation, 
structure and mass. PDS456 provides us with a nearby analogue to rare hot 
dusty AGN being found at z~2-3, and is the most dramatically active 
galaxy within its distance from us: a key to investigating the most 
extreme AGNs at the peak of the AGN/star-formation activity. </prp:abstract>
